<br>
As far as the money for a hard drive goes, X-Box wins.  Kinda sucks to have to cough up so much for one for the PS2.  On the bright side, I never have to worry about having a broken hard drive in my PS2.  Personal preference, I suppose.<br>
<br>
The lack of a net adapter in the PS2 kinda bugs me, but I haven't bought any games yet that would support it anyway.  Truthfully, if I want online gaming, I'm gonna do it on my PC anyway.<br>
<br>
As far as the old &quot;better hardware, better graphics&quot; thing goes, I'm a bit jaded after the Dreamcast and N64.  Those two systems, along with the Saturn, 32X, and Jaguar proved to me that hardware alone can't keep a market alive.  If good games keep rolling out for the X-Box, then it might survive.  Otherwise, it's gonna join the ranks of &quot;could've been&quot; systems.<br>
<br>
On the subject of memory cards, those 8MB PS2 cards are awesome compared to the old 1MB PS1 cards.  They changed the file system so that you aren't limited to 15 files anymore.  The file size is what determines how much card space it takes, as opposed to the old &quot;1 block&quot; idea.  The 8MB goes a long way--even after loading 2 megs of updated DVD software onto my mem card, I still have over 5 megs free after all my saved games.<br>
<br>
I bought a PS2 because I knew the games would be good quality, and there would be plenty to choose from.  It's a sure bet.  The bad thing is that you get less &quot;oomph&quot; for your $300.  As far as specs go, the X-Box is the better system, but it's also a bit of a gamble.  While Microsoft won't be going under anytime soon, they have a history of ditching products that they don't think are profitable or that they consider to be outdated.<br>
<br>
